1
00:00:05,110 --> 00:00:16,945
A Detailed Guided Meditation Instructions on how to practice Vipassana Bhavana insight meditation as taught by the Mahasi Sayadaw of Burma.

2
00:00:16,964 --> 00:00:20,388
Firstly, we must settle our body into a meditative posture.

3
00:00:21,210 --> 00:00:29,060
Some sit on chairs, others use kneeling stools, but the usual position is to sit on the floor with a cushion in a cross-legged posture.

4
00:00:30,501 --> 00:00:34,948
Your hands should rest on your lap, preferably one on top of the other.

5
00:00:37,307 --> 00:00:40,591
Now whatever posture you adopt it should at first feel comfortable.

6
00:00:41,853 --> 00:00:45,517
Then make sure the spine is straight though keeping its natural curvature.

7
00:00:47,037 --> 00:00:49,941
It's best not to lean against anything for this will induce sleep.

8
00:00:52,503 --> 00:01:04,176
Now imagine a puppet string running from the base of the spine to the top of the head and it being gently pulled up so that all the vertebrae separate and there's a feeling of growing tall and light.

9
00:01:05,201 --> 00:01:09,365
A feeling of energy running up the spine without any tension or tightness.

10
00:01:11,427 --> 00:01:13,308
And the head should feel balanced on top.

11
00:01:15,831 --> 00:01:18,694
Now just let everything relax off that central column.

12
00:01:20,594 --> 00:01:24,198
Here we can help ourselves relax with some simple exercises.

13
00:01:25,560 --> 00:01:30,965
Firstly, let's see how relaxed we can become by simply telling muscles to relax.

14
00:01:31,905 --> 00:01:34,888
Start from the top of the head and go down the rest of the body

15
00:01:35,441 --> 00:01:37,524
relaxing muscles as best you can.

16
00:01:39,066 --> 00:02:03,474
So start at the top of the head, come down over the brow, the eyes, the cheeks, the jaw, especially the jaw, the neck, shoulders, arms, and hands.

17
00:02:04,923 --> 00:02:08,888
Just feel everything getting heavier as tension stops supporting them.

18
00:02:11,471 --> 00:02:12,913
Now go back to the chest.

19
00:02:14,294 --> 00:02:14,975
Relax it.

20
00:02:17,399 --> 00:02:21,524
Go down the body to the stomach, to the abdomen.

21
00:02:22,525 --> 00:02:24,347
Just relaxing as best as you can.

22
00:02:25,949 --> 00:02:29,614
And finally, just feel your legs heavy on the floor.

23
00:02:32,259 --> 00:02:43,836
Superficial surface tension should now be released if only a little, but we may feel a deeper level of tension more habitual and therefore not easy to relax by a mental volition.

24
00:02:45,478 --> 00:02:48,481
We can use a second technique here of muscular tension.

25
00:02:50,044 --> 00:02:56,532
Where you feel tension tense the muscles in that area as hard as you can and release them slowly.

26
00:02:58,276 --> 00:03:00,799
This is especially good for tension in the face.

27
00:03:02,111 --> 00:03:04,556
Just screw up the face as much as you can now.

28
00:03:06,237 --> 00:03:06,778
Hold it.

29
00:03:09,021 --> 00:03:09,723
And relax.

30
00:03:14,710 --> 00:03:15,831
Now let's try that again.

31
00:03:17,174 --> 00:03:17,715
Hold it.

32
00:03:19,978 --> 00:03:20,419
Hold it.

33
00:03:22,521 --> 00:03:23,263
And relax.

34
00:03:25,586 --> 00:03:27,669
It's also good for the neck and shoulders.

35
00:03:28,210 --> 00:03:30,312
Just tighten up that whole area now.

36
00:03:32,992 --> 00:03:33,574
Hold it.

37
00:03:36,736 --> 00:03:38,158
And relax slowly.

38
00:03:41,122 --> 00:03:41,983
Let's try that again.

39
00:03:42,002 --> 00:03:43,544
Tighten up the whole area.

40
00:03:43,585 --> 00:03:46,989
Neck and shoulders.

41
00:03:48,169 --> 00:03:48,730
Hold it.

42
00:03:50,992 --> 00:03:52,594
And just relax slowly.

43
00:03:56,118 --> 00:04:01,024
A third technique is best for tensions felt in the chest, though it has an effect on the whole body.

44
00:04:01,525 --> 00:04:02,645
Controlled breathing.

45
00:04:03,772 --> 00:04:13,947
Take a slow, deep in-breath, fill the lungs to capacity, hold for as long as comfortable, and just let the whole ribcage fall quickly, expelling all the air.

46
00:04:15,169 --> 00:04:20,497
Then wait for the next breath to arise naturally, and this will prevent hyperventilation.

47
00:04:21,959 --> 00:04:31,872
So now let's take in a deep breath, hold it, and just let it go.

48
00:04:37,776 --> 00:04:38,798
Let's try that again.

49
00:04:38,838 --> 00:04:39,899
Take a deep breath.

50
00:04:44,964 --> 00:04:45,485
Hold it.

51
00:04:48,189 --> 00:04:49,149
And just let it go.

52
00:04:49,170 --> 00:04:55,898
Hopefully you will have developed a deep relaxation.

53
00:04:56,619 --> 00:05:00,843
So now we should find ourselves in a posture highly conducive for meditation.

54
00:05:01,824 --> 00:05:04,408
The spine should be energised but not tense.

55
00:05:04,944 --> 00:05:10,454
The rest of the body should feel relaxed, hanging, as it were, off this central column of the spine.

56
00:05:11,696 --> 00:05:19,007
And the head should be gently poised on top, symbolizing the balance between physical alertness and relaxation.

57
00:05:20,588 --> 00:05:30,564
So now, for a few moments, let's feel this posture as a whole, and recognize its qualities of alert energy and yet calm relaxations.

58
00:06:34,872 --> 00:06:43,084
Now we need to develop the same sense of energetic alertness and relaxed calmness in the mind, and to achieve this we use the breath.

59
00:06:44,466 --> 00:06:51,576
Place your attention on the abdomen and feel its rising and falling motion as you breathe naturally.

60
00:06:52,778 --> 00:06:55,182
Please note this is not a breathing technique.

61
00:06:55,663 --> 00:06:57,605
The breath should not be interfered with.

62
00:06:59,560 --> 00:07:07,216
Now it may be that the breath is not obvious to you at the abdomen, in which case see if you can feel it at the chest, rising and falling.

63
00:07:08,358 --> 00:07:14,630
The breath at the nostrils may also be used, but for the Mahasi technique it is preferable to use the abdomen.

64
00:07:15,913 --> 00:07:18,278
See now which one is most obvious to you.

65
00:07:34,137 --> 00:07:38,725
Now whichever place you've chosen, this is your primary object of meditation.

66
00:07:39,285 --> 00:07:43,773
This means you will use this place to establish an alert and calm awareness.

67
00:07:45,154 --> 00:07:59,098
If you move from one place to another, say from the nose to the abdomen, this will undermine your ability to become concentrated, that is, the ability to watch with an alert but calm attention without flitting away.

68
00:08:01,627 --> 00:08:11,261
If you're watching the breath process at the abdomen or chest, observe the movement, the rising and falling, and use a noting word to still the thinking process.

69
00:08:12,322 --> 00:08:18,810
With the in-breath, note rising, rising, and with the out-breath, note falling, falling.

70
00:08:20,372 --> 00:08:24,959
After the out-breath, there's a rest, and there's danger that the mind will run away on fantasies.

71
00:08:26,100 --> 00:08:29,406
Now, to stop this happening, we choose a touch point.

72
00:08:30,483 --> 00:08:35,711
It may be the feeling of your hands on your lap, or the feelings of your legs on the floor.

73
00:08:37,033 --> 00:08:38,535
Choose what is most obvious.

74
00:08:44,725 --> 00:08:56,845
So as you feel the abdomen or chest rising with the in-breath, feel those feelings, watch them closely and point your attention directly at them, noting, rising, rising.

75
00:08:58,528 --> 00:09:06,077
In the same way as you feel the abdomen or chest falling with the out-breath, feel the feelings, the sensations of the movement.

76
00:09:06,658 --> 00:09:10,101
Watch them intently and note falling, falling.

77
00:09:12,205 --> 00:09:16,470
If there's a pause before the in-breath, note a touching point.

78
00:09:17,250 --> 00:09:19,894
Touching, touching, touching.

79
00:09:22,115 --> 00:09:27,743
Now be sure as soon as the in-breath starts to return immediately to the abdomen or the chest.

80
00:09:29,865 --> 00:09:45,822
If you're concentrating at the nostrils, it's the same, except it's more appropriate to use the noting words in-in, out-out, while remembering to concentrate on the sensations at the nostrils or the upper lip, wherever the passage of air is felt most acutely.

81
00:09:47,804 --> 00:09:51,369
Please note it doesn't matter how many times you say the noting word.

82
00:09:52,110 --> 00:09:52,990
Once may be enough.

83
00:09:53,731 --> 00:09:59,738
What is important is to be attentive to the feelings or sensations as they arise.

84
00:10:00,190 --> 00:10:02,312
The word itself is of little importance.

85
00:10:02,993 --> 00:10:07,538
It's just a simple and very effective way to stop the mind from wandering.

86
00:10:08,720 --> 00:10:14,125
What you must pay attention to are all the sensations caused by the process of breathing.

87
00:10:16,268 --> 00:10:20,113
Now you may find that your mind wanders off on thoughts and fantasies.

88
00:10:20,673 --> 00:10:28,442
When you wake up out of them, just note thinking, thinking, or dreaming, dreaming, once or twice, and then quickly and firmly say,

89
00:10:28,743 --> 00:10:31,585
go back to watching the sensations of breathing.

90
00:10:32,505 --> 00:10:34,467
But you mustn't be rough or forceful.

91
00:10:35,328 --> 00:10:38,390
Training the mind is a bit like training a puppy dog to sit.

92
00:10:39,192 --> 00:10:42,495
When it gets up, you have to pat it down kindly but firmly.

93
00:10:42,835 --> 00:10:45,417
If you get angry and hit it, it will just want to run away.

94
00:10:47,739 --> 00:10:54,725
So now, let's practice this breathing meditation for a while, observing and noting all the sensations.

95
00:10:56,706 --> 00:10:57,567
Rising...

96
00:10:58,004 --> 00:11:00,318
Falling, touching.

97
00:14:52,988 --> 00:15:03,518
If your mind is wandering, note what it's doing, dreaming, thinking, worrying, and so on, and bring it back gently but firmly to the breath.

98
00:15:03,538 --> 00:15:09,004
If you feel sleepy, put more energy into the spine, sit tall, but not tense.

99
00:15:10,465 --> 00:15:15,129
This part of the meditation is mainly concerned with establishing concentration.

100
00:15:16,150 --> 00:15:21,155
It's normal to spend a good ten minutes doing this until the mind becomes fairly still.

101
00:15:21,928 --> 00:15:29,557
at least until gross restlessness has gone, and you can watch the object, in this case the breath, fairly constantly.

102
00:15:31,419 --> 00:15:35,583
We use the breath because it's a neutral feeling, it doesn't excite or depress us.

103
00:15:36,404 --> 00:15:43,133
So the mind becomes still and moves to a point of concentration by way of calm and peacefulness.

104
00:15:44,735 --> 00:15:51,361
This is different from the sort of concentration we get when we are doing something engrossing, such as watching a film,

105
00:15:51,679 --> 00:15:53,261
or having to do a job carefully.

106
00:15:54,363 --> 00:16:02,072
That depends upon stimulation, but the concentration we need for insight must arise out of a quiet and still mind.

107
00:16:03,253 --> 00:16:13,384
And when this sort of concentrated, quiet mind is established, we find another faculty becomes prominent, our intuitive intelligence, pāññā.

108
00:16:15,787 --> 00:16:19,071
Sometimes, when you're trying to listen to shortwave radio,

109
00:16:19,269 --> 00:16:23,197
There's so much interference, it's hard to hear exactly what's being said.

110
00:16:23,216 --> 00:16:26,802
Once the fuzz goes, everything becomes clear.

111
00:16:27,663 --> 00:16:30,828
So it is with panya, our intuitive intelligence.

112
00:16:31,791 --> 00:16:43,269
Once the heart is calm and concentrated, and thinking and imagining has stopped, the intuitive intelligence is able to see and understand clearly what's going on.

113
00:16:46,438 --> 00:16:59,235
So now, what we have to do is establish this concentrated attentiveness, alive with intelligence, satipanya, not just on the breath, but on anything that comes into our field of awareness.

114
00:17:01,217 --> 00:17:03,520
The example I like is that of a bird watcher.

115
00:17:04,261 --> 00:17:06,104
They sit in a so-called hide.

116
00:17:06,805 --> 00:17:09,288
They hide there, hidden from the birds they are watching.

117
00:17:10,269 --> 00:17:14,775
In this way, the birds are not disturbed, and their natural habits can be observed.

118
00:17:15,548 --> 00:17:23,756
All the knowledge, such as of feeding, nesting, mating, and so on, comes by just observing, merely watching.

119
00:17:24,696 --> 00:17:35,708
In this way, this ability to be simply observers, interested to discover the true nature of our body, mind, and heart, is the key to spiritual insight.

120
00:17:36,788 --> 00:17:41,493
But this watching, please understand clearly, is not a searching for something.

121
00:17:42,494 --> 00:17:44,576
We are not looking for something.

122
00:17:45,146 --> 00:18:01,467
We're just non-interfering observers, just looking at whatever comes into our field of awareness, just watching whatever arises right here and now, while it's happening, without any thoughts about it or questions.

123
00:18:04,371 --> 00:18:07,574
So we begin by establishing attentiveness on the breath.

124
00:18:08,496 --> 00:18:13,521
Should a sound be heard, we avert to it immediately, noting hearing, hearing.

125
00:18:14,303 --> 00:18:14,563
Now,

126
00:18:14,797 --> 00:18:17,859
try to catch the quality of the sound at the very eardrum.

127
00:18:18,681 --> 00:18:28,551
In this way, we'll stop the mind flying out, as it were, to the object, such as a chirping bird or passing car, and set up a whole train of imaginative thoughts.

128
00:18:29,373 --> 00:18:30,273
The same with smell.

129
00:18:30,973 --> 00:18:34,417
Note it as smelling, smelling, right there in the nostrils.

130
00:18:35,519 --> 00:18:43,587
And again with any sensations on the body, such as itching and prickling, just note itching, itching, prickling, prickling, right there,

131
00:18:43,821 --> 00:18:47,685
where the sensations are felt, and plunge your attention into them.

132
00:18:49,769 --> 00:18:56,916
Then there are feelings that arise in the body, such as heat and cold, heaviness and lightness, all sorts of discomforts and pleasures.

133
00:18:57,978 --> 00:19:05,386
A particular word, such as heat or cold, can be used where appropriate, otherwise a general word, feeling, can be used.

134
00:19:07,588 --> 00:19:13,355
Now, it's important we don't react to these feelings unless they are too severe to tolerate.

135
00:19:13,825 --> 00:19:16,868
for to react to them will lead us into restlessness.

136
00:19:17,730 --> 00:19:23,396
And do remember the noting word is a technique we use to keep the attention steady on the object.

137
00:19:23,857 --> 00:19:32,509
In other words, it controls the thinking faculty, but the attention itself should bury itself into the actual sensations.

138
00:19:35,432 --> 00:19:39,057
Again, there are feelings in the body arising from moods and emotions.

139
00:19:39,678 --> 00:19:42,381
Dislikable ones, such as fear and depression,

140
00:19:42,714 --> 00:19:44,817
and likeable ones such as joy and love.

141
00:19:45,999 --> 00:20:04,538
We can use specific words here, such as love, guilt, and so on, but all the time feeling fully the mood or emotion, the actual feelings wherever they occur, such as in the chest or stomach.

142
00:20:04,559 --> 00:20:06,382
Finally, there are thoughts and images.

143
00:20:07,442 --> 00:20:10,926
Note these as thinking or imagining, and they will stop.

144
00:20:11,467 --> 00:20:12,147
Otherwise,

145
00:20:12,414 --> 00:20:16,898
They will carry you off onto a daydream, sometimes for the whole of the meditation period.

146
00:20:18,181 --> 00:20:20,202
And be especially aware of the judging mind.

147
00:20:20,482 --> 00:20:24,247
That's terrible, that's good, that's bad, that's nice, and so on.

148
00:20:24,826 --> 00:20:27,289
Don't correct or interfere with such thoughts.

149
00:20:27,869 --> 00:20:31,094
Just acknowledge them and note judging, judging.

150
00:20:32,955 --> 00:20:39,122
We're not trying to become spectators, getting involved in all the mental play, supporting this against that.

151
00:20:40,083 --> 00:20:42,404
We must take the position of an observer.

152
00:20:42,757 --> 00:20:49,625
an objective observer, just allowing all the play to unfold right there before our very gaze.

153
00:20:50,926 --> 00:21:01,338
All the time we're trying to maintain that separation, that distance, that detachment from what's going on in the body, mind and heart.

154
00:21:01,358 --> 00:21:07,306
We observe all these psychophysical events as something other, as if belonging to someone else.

155
00:21:08,346 --> 00:21:11,109
In this way we can investigate objectively.

156
00:21:11,916 --> 00:21:17,727
So whatever is offered, a sensation, a feeling, a thought, just watch it carefully.

157
00:21:19,609 --> 00:21:26,362
So now, let's sit tall, and with keen interest, let's watch the flow of physical and mental phenomena.

158
00:21:27,984 --> 00:21:29,488
Begin always with the breath.

159
00:21:30,890 --> 00:21:34,296
Rising, falling, touching.

160
00:24:35,192 --> 00:24:44,346
If the mind is wandering, note what it's doing, dreaming, thinking, worrying, and so on, and bring it back to the breath, firmly but gently.

161
00:24:45,469 --> 00:24:57,948
If there's sloth, energize the spine, re-establish the posture, slowly, very slowly, or you may disturb your concentration, noting the whole movement, straightening, straightening.

162
00:25:00,592 --> 00:25:02,414
Sometimes there's a lot of pain.

163
00:25:03,391 --> 00:25:05,794
aching and tension comes up in the body.

164
00:25:05,834 --> 00:25:09,980
This won't be due to posture so long as the posture is correct.

165
00:25:11,121 --> 00:25:18,731
They'll probably be caused by unresolved emotions and mental states that have until now been suppressed out of consciousness.

166
00:25:20,073 --> 00:25:23,738
It's important to relax around them and develop an attitude of interest.

167
00:25:24,618 --> 00:25:32,470
Such discomfort, sometimes severe, may continue throughout a whole sitting or for many sittings until it resolves itself.

168
00:25:33,242 --> 00:25:38,108
and it may be that the underlying reason, such as an emotion, will not manifest itself.

169
00:25:38,990 --> 00:25:42,976
Just the passing of the discomfort will mean that the curing has taken place.

170
00:25:44,196 --> 00:25:58,895
We need to develop patience to bear this sort of thing and use the opportunity to see pain as pain, just sensations, and to separate out the suffering which is the aversion or fear we feel towards them.

171
00:26:00,317 --> 00:26:03,182
We make both sides, the painful sensations...

172
00:26:03,517 --> 00:26:08,846
and the mental attitudes, objects to be noted, observed, and understood.

173
00:26:10,027 --> 00:26:15,036
So, keep noting, keep observing, maintaining a sharp attentiveness.

174
00:26:16,017 --> 00:26:21,085
If you get lost, start again with the breath, your home base and anchor.

175
00:26:23,628 --> 00:26:25,392
Always begin again with the breath.

176
00:26:26,894 --> 00:26:30,299
Rising, falling, touching.

177
00:30:56,787 --> 00:31:03,656
If your mind is wandering, bring it back firmly but gently to the primary object of our meditation, the breath.

178
00:31:04,959 --> 00:31:11,568
If there's tiredness or dullness, raise energy up the spine by sitting tall, though not tense, remember.

179
00:31:12,570 --> 00:31:16,276
Be especially aware of tension around the shoulders, neck and jaw.

180
00:31:21,124 --> 00:31:25,410
Here we are sitting within ourselves, as it were, watching the inner films.

181
00:31:26,048 --> 00:31:29,612
The body, mind and heart display themselves just as they want.

182
00:31:29,752 --> 00:31:30,814
We don't interfere.

183
00:31:31,875 --> 00:31:34,077
It's a natural process of revelation.

184
00:31:35,019 --> 00:31:40,285
In time, many things may arise out of the subconscious which have long been suppressed.

185
00:31:41,246 --> 00:31:46,712
They'll reveal themselves when the time is right and the time is right when we'll be ready to accept them.

186
00:31:48,134 --> 00:31:52,279
In this way, insight meditation brings about a psychotherapy.

187
00:31:53,020 --> 00:31:55,683
Even painful traumatic memories from childhood

188
00:31:56,018 --> 00:32:02,489
will be eventually cleared out of the system, and with them all the neuroses and tensions they've caused.

189
00:32:04,011 --> 00:32:10,682
All we have to do to attain this purification of the heart is to remain steadfast at our observation post.

190
00:32:13,909 --> 00:32:19,498
Now, although the cleansing of our psychology will happen naturally, it's not the aim of our meditation.

191
00:32:20,440 --> 00:32:21,721
The aim of our practice...

192
00:32:21,938 --> 00:32:26,722
is to go to the deepest levels to see why suffering arises in the first place.

193
00:32:29,006 --> 00:32:33,651
One way is to note the relationship we have to whatever is being observed.

194
00:32:34,311 --> 00:32:42,161
The mind constantly jumps from liking to disliking wanting what it likes not wanting what it dislikes.

195
00:32:42,862 --> 00:32:51,050
This sort of involvement is simply a way in which we try to find happiness in pleasurable states and escape unhappiness

196
00:32:51,352 --> 00:32:53,634
by running away from unpleasurable states.

197
00:32:55,218 --> 00:33:05,412
This constant oscillation, this ricocheting from greed to aversion and back to greed, this is what the Buddha taught as the cause of our suffering in the Second Noble Truth.

198
00:33:06,834 --> 00:33:21,055
So, as pleasurable or unpleasurable objects arise, we must keenly note this secondary reaction of grabbing at them or pushing them away, sometimes turning away in fear, the twin of aversion,

199
00:33:22,267 --> 00:33:31,118
In this way, this reaction will cool down and even stop, and we shall experience a deeply satisfying equanimous mind.

200
00:33:32,339 --> 00:33:37,267
And this in turn will allow us to investigate deeper into the causes of suffering.

201
00:33:38,909 --> 00:33:43,394
So let all that pain and pleasure surface and express itself.

202
00:33:44,296 --> 00:33:47,940
Watch the reaction, the grabbing, the aversion, the fear.

203
00:33:50,644 --> 00:33:52,205
Begin again with the breath.

204
00:33:53,619 --> 00:33:57,166
Rising, falling, touching.

205
00:36:57,371 --> 00:37:04,139
If your mind is wandering, note what it's been doing and re-establish your concentration on the breath.

206
00:37:05,581 --> 00:37:09,505
If you're sleepy, sit tall and raise energy up the spine.

207
00:37:09,545 --> 00:37:25,302
As we begin to deepen our awareness of all the phenomena arising in our body, mind and heart, we'll become increasingly aware of what the Buddha called the three characteristics of existence.

208
00:37:26,717 --> 00:37:28,840
The first is the fact of transience.

209
00:37:29,882 --> 00:37:32,644
Everything is arising only to pass away.

210
00:37:34,246 --> 00:37:37,050
The second is the difficult teaching of non-self.

211
00:37:38,632 --> 00:37:44,219
As we watch all these mental and physical phenomena, we'll notice they arise of themselves.

212
00:37:44,900 --> 00:37:46,282
There's no one controlling them.

213
00:37:47,224 --> 00:37:49,567
They have their own life, their own energy.

214
00:37:51,047 --> 00:37:55,594
At times the body, mind and heart may seem distant, something other,

215
00:37:57,143 --> 00:38:08,074
Before we talked of my sensations, my thoughts, my emotions, but now we find ourselves pointing at them, as it were, through the noting technique.

216
00:38:09,315 --> 00:38:13,217
There's a sensation, there's a thought, there's a feeling.

217
00:38:15,079 --> 00:38:19,644
We're slowly moving away from a relationship of identity and possession.

218
00:38:20,945 --> 00:38:25,210
I am my seeing, I am what I think, I am what I feel.

219
00:38:25,594 --> 00:38:28,699
I have a body, I have a mind, I have a heart.

220
00:38:29,840 --> 00:38:33,146
Instead, we're moving towards a position of detachment.

221
00:38:34,128 --> 00:38:37,052
This is the beginning of the experience of non-self.

222
00:38:38,173 --> 00:38:44,682
We discover that the psychophysical organism we call me doesn't constitute anything substantial.

223
00:38:45,364 --> 00:38:49,489
It's just made up of many parts that work in unison, just like a car.

224
00:38:50,210 --> 00:38:52,614
But there's no core to it, no substance.

225
00:38:54,804 --> 00:39:07,579
Thirdly, as we've noticed, whenever we do fall into a relationship of attachment, desire or aversion to the body, mind and heart, of identifying and possessing, suffering follows.

226
00:39:08,699 --> 00:39:12,123
This is the third characteristic of unsatisfactoriness.

227
00:39:14,206 --> 00:39:21,454
We should develop an attitude towards the body, mind and heart as one who rents a house, not as one who owns one.

228
00:39:23,105 --> 00:39:39,463
It is the observation of these three characteristics of transience, insubstantiality and unsatisfactoriness that brings about the spiritual insights that releases consciousness from its delusions and leads to liberation from all suffering.

229
00:39:40,923 --> 00:39:44,507
And it is this practice of vipassana which is the tool we use.

230
00:39:46,389 --> 00:39:51,576
This bare attentiveness, simply observing all that arises and passes away,

231
00:39:52,788 --> 00:40:22,034
this choiceless awareness that does not control or manipulate, this impartial watchfulness that does not question or judge, this intuitive introspection, fully experiencing each mental and bodily phenomenon as it really is, this is the faculty of intuitive awareness, satipanya, the very faculty that will eventually bring the realization of nibbana, the unborn,

232
00:40:22,318 --> 00:40:25,824
the unbecome, the unmade, the unconditioned.

233
00:40:27,226 --> 00:40:34,378
All we have to do is watch, just observe, whatever arises as it arises and passes away.

234
00:40:37,784 --> 00:40:40,047
So let's begin again with the breath.

235
00:40:41,369 --> 00:40:44,934
Rising, falling, touching.

236
00:42:53,197 --> 00:43:04,170
During daily life, to sit like this even for a few moments, long enough to re-establish a calm and alert attentiveness, will stop our emotions from snowballing.

237
00:43:05,090 --> 00:43:07,132
It will undermine the causes of stress.

238
00:43:07,994 --> 00:43:11,297
Just 15 seconds may be enough to re-establish our center.

239
00:43:12,458 --> 00:43:18,804
With practice, this can become a regular state of mind, instead of something that comes only under special conditions.

240
00:43:20,126 --> 00:43:22,429
This calm heart and alert mind

241
00:43:22,746 --> 00:43:26,112
is the state we ought to be in all the time, even under stress.

242
00:43:28,054 --> 00:43:33,702
It is within this inner environment that this intuitive awareness, satipanya, can operate.

243
00:43:34,443 --> 00:43:39,510
Otherwise it becomes lost, drowned and controlled by runaway thoughts and emotions.

244
00:43:40,411 --> 00:43:44,476
Constantly make the effort to regain and maintain this inner posture.

245
00:43:45,378 --> 00:43:47,762
This is to live fully consciously.

246
00:43:48,782 --> 00:43:49,563
And in this way,

247
00:43:49,882 --> 00:43:58,791
The practice of vipassana, insight meditation, will seep into every moment of our lives, and we will be rewarded with great benefits.

248
00:44:02,175 --> 00:44:08,882
Now, when we come to the end of a meditation period, it's best not to just jump out of it, but come out slowly.

249
00:44:08,922 --> 00:44:16,331
First, opening the eyes and taking in the light, and gently swaying from side to side.

250
00:44:17,193 --> 00:44:17,592
Then,

251
00:44:18,097 --> 00:44:26,052
rising slowly and mindfully, and in this way our intuitive mindfulness, satipanya, will be maintained.

252
00:44:29,239 --> 00:44:39,277
May you be well, may you be happy, may you soon be liberated of all your suffering, may you experience the peace and bliss of nibbana.

